article.headline: Seattle doesn't bounce back, loses to Cleveland
article.linkText: Rockers take advantage of fatigued, lethargic Storm
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Sue Bird crumpled up the final boxscore and tossed it, then teammate Simone Edwards copied her and spiked her own stat sheet to the ground. A night after everything went right for the Seattle Storm, everything seemed to go wrong in their 62-58 defeat against the Cleveland Rockers on Friday. Seattle (9-11) had its fourth-lowest point total of the season after scoring 45 points in the first half of its 79-60 victory against the defending champion Los Angeles Sparks on Thursday. Bird, the No. 1 draft choice this year and a starter in the All-Star Game on Monday, now has 11 more defeats this summer than she had all season in leading Connecticut to an undefeated year and the NCAA title. ''We're going to have to win a lot of games to make the playoffs,'' said Bird, who had 17 points and seven assists. ''This is where we are. You've got to sleep in the bed you make for yourself.'' Ann Wauters scored 16 points and Penny Taylor had nine of her 12 in the second half to help the Rockers snap a six-game losing streak. Chasity Melvin had 12 points and 12 rebounds for Cleveland (7-12) and Merlakia Jones had 10 points and five rebounds. Wauters was 8-for-8 from the free throw line and Taylor scored her team's first seven points in the second half. Rockers coach Dan Hughes praised his team's defense against a team he thinks should make the playoffs. ''We're just trying to get our feet on the ground,'' he said. ''We've faced a lot of ups and downs. I'm impressed with Seattle. I'm impressed with Lauren Jackson and Sue Bird. This was our best defensive game.'' The 6-foot-5 Jackson scored 10 of her 22 points over the final 7:06 for Seattle. The Storm outscored the Rockers 8-4 to start the second half to pull to 29-28, then Taylor made a 3-pointer and Wauters converted two free throws. The Rockers dominated the rest of the way, going 12-for-23 from the field in the second half to shoot 40.8 percent for the game. The Storm shot 39 percent. ''I thought we looked fatigued, I thought we looked lethargic and I thought we missed Michelle Marciniak's energy off the bench,'' Seattle coach Lin Dunn said. Marciniak, a reserve guard, was suspended by the league along with Los Angeles' Latasha Byears for their part in a fight Thursday. Byears was suspended for two games and fined $1,000, while Marciniak got a one-game suspension and a $500 fine. ''I feel really bad. I can't tell you what it feels like to be sitting here when I'm supposed to be at the gym right now,'' Marciniak said in a phone interview from her home. ''It's very disappointing to me. I've got mixed emotions about it. I know they talk about retaliation and I saw the film many, many, many times today. I don't know the difference in acting in self-defense and retaliation. What do you take and what don't you take as a player? Where do you draw the line?'' She plans to appeal the fine. ''We learned a lesson on what can happen if you retaliate,'' Dunn said. Cleveland led 25-20 at halftime behind 12 points from Wauters. The Storm made only nine first-half field goals and the Rockers just eight. Both teams had seven turnovers. Notes
Taylor left the game with 1:06 left in the first half with a sprained right ankle, but returned after halftime. ... Melvin's 12 rebounds matched her career high. ... The Storm were outrebounded 31-27.
